Decreasing density reduces air resistance, allowing fly balls to fly a longer distance and turning a warning track fly ball into a home run.  The decrease in density is also the reason that aircraft have a harder time taking off on hot days:https://t.co/rfVxLPBpKT

This is intuitively simple: in a parcel of air, as the molecules get warmer, they move around faster and bump into each other harder, and that increases the average distance between them, corresponding to decreased density.

It's related to warmer temperatures.  If you remember high school chemistry, the ideal gas law (PV = nRT) tells you that density (n/V) is proportional to pressure divided by temperature (P/T).  As temperature increases, density decreases.

But a baseline level of catastrophe is now baked in - ie guaranteed in our lifetimes. Even in the very best case scenarios, there is now no future that does not include huge levels of suffering for many millions of people, and major disruption for each and every one of us. /19
Can we solve it? Yes and no. Scientists tell us that there is a ton we can do to avoid the worst impacts (though it isn‚Äôt currently happening at anywhere near the required speed and scale). /18

Again - and I cannot stress this enough - all this is mainstream scientific consensus, not the lunatic fringe. There are scientists on the extreme edge, but this is not that. You really don‚Äôt want to know what the extreme scientists are saying. /17
And it doesn‚Äôt stop there. We are on track for 2.7 to 3 degrees by the end of the century, when my kids will be in their old age. What happens then is pure nightmare fuel. /16
We are projected to hit 2 degrees by the late 2040‚Äôs/early 2050‚Äôs, or right around my 75th birthday. /15

While 2 degrees is not expected to be human extinction level territory, it will create a world that is in many ways unrecognizable from the one I‚Äôve grown up in. If you thought COVID was disruptive, it will pale by comparison to 2 degrees. /14

2 degrees of warming is expected to be catastrophic, with civilization scale risks. This is why the Paris agreement, agreed to by virtually every country on the planet, aims to keep warming below 2 degrees of warming. /13

We won‚Äôt actually be considered to be beyond 1.5 until we average that level of warming over a 10-year period, which is projected to happen in the early 2030‚Äôs. In other words, we‚Äôll be out of the ‚Äúsafe zone‚Äù before I‚Äôm 60. /12
With the return of El Ni√±o, which produces our warmest years, many scientists expect that 2024 - next year - will be the first year that we breach the 1.5 degree ‚Äúsafe‚Äù limit. /11

Scientific consensus is that 1.5 degrees of warming represents the ‚Äúsafe‚Äù limit of warming. (Though they have also been shocked by the extremes we are seeing at just 1.2, leading many to conclude that 1.5 is not nearly as safe as they once thought.) /10
But obsession does not equal extremism. Like I said, my views fall squarely within scientific consensus. /9
So yeah, I‚Äôm pretty obsessed with what is happening with our planet. And I think that anyone who truly understood what is happening would be, and should be. /8
Once that began to sink in, I could no longer look away. I realized everything I was expecting for my own future, and that of my kids, was wrong. /7

And as I learned the science behind climate change, the depth, scope and imminence of the problem began to sink in. And I realized that the awful consequences are coming, not just in my children‚Äôs lifetime, which would be terrible enough, but in my lifetime. /6

By addressing these sustainability challenges and implementing solutions, FPOs in India can build resilient and sustainable businesses, improve the livelihoods of farmers, and contribute to a more sustainable and equitable food system.

FPOs can also invest in capacity building and training programs for farmers to improve their skills, knowledge, and understanding of sustainable farming practices, market trends, and value chain development.

Another challenge is the lack of access to finance and credit. FPOs can overcome this by partnering with financial institutions and government programs to access credit, insurance, and other financial services.

FPOs can also promote agroforestry by integrating trees into their farming systems. This can help reduce soil erosion, enhance biodiversity, and provide additional income opportunities through non-timber forest products.

In addition, FPOs can promote biodiversity and conservation by protecting natural resources such as forests, wildlife, and wetlands. This can help mitigate the impact of climate change and provide additional income opportunities for farmers.

FPOs can also adopt technology such as mobile apps, e-commerce platforms, and blockchain to improve supply chain management, traceability, and transparency. This can help build consumer trust and increase market demand for their products.

Another challenge is the lack of access to markets and value chains. FPOs can overcome this by partnering with food processing companies, exporters, and retailers to increase market access and improve the value chain for their products.

FPOs can also invest in rainwater harvesting, drip irrigation, and other water conservation measures to reduce water wastage and increase efficiency. This can help farmers cope with droughts and water scarcity.

To address these challenges, FPOs can adopt sustainable farming practices such as crop rotation, intercropping, and organic farming. These practices can help conserve soil fertility, reduce water consumption, and enhance crop productivity.

Farmer Producer Organizations (FPOs) in India face several sustainability challenges, including climate change, soil degradation, and water scarcity. These challenges have a direct impact on the livelihoods of farmers and the long-term viability of FPOs.
